3.Use variables, conditionals, loops in scripts.
In this script I can use the variable “NAME” and then if condition in this condition statement file is exist it print the if part or  else part will be display 
I have used For loop condition  to display the numbers
#! /bin/bash

NAME="anil"
echo "username $NAME"

if [ -f /etc/passwd ]; then
   echo "File exists"
else
   echo "File is not exist"
fi

for i in 1 2 3
do 
  echo "number: $i"
done

./anil.sh
username anil
File exists
number: 1
number: 2
number: 3

4.Automate log cleanup or backup tasks.
#! /bin/bash

find /var/log -type f -mtime +7 -delete 
tar -cvzf backup.tar /home/anil/Documents



5.Make script executable and run it.
We have check the permission of the file , if execute permission is not then give execute permission for the script use the below command
Chmod +x file name or chmod 777 filename
 chmod +x anil.sh
 ll anil.sh
-rwxrwxr-x 1 anil anil 121 Jan 21 16:15 anil.sh*
./anil.sh

6.Redirect output to files.
We can use > to redirect the output   to file
>> to redirect the output to append the existing the input file

 echo $PWD >putta.txt
 cat putta.txt
/home/anil



